<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-02-20T05:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-02-20T05:00:00-05:00" n="714" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d714">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/2–2045: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Atcheson</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-02-20T17:00:00+07:00">February
                                    20, 1945—5 p.m.</date>
                                <lb/> [Received February 20—2:45 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>261. On February 16, General Hurley made informal oral approach to T. V.
                            Soong in regard to the possibility of amnesty for political <pb facs="1004" n="994" xml:id="pg_994"/> prisoners in Sinkiang
                            (ReDeptel 181, February 2); the following day Soong informed General
                            Hurley that he had referred matter to Generalissimo.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Atcheson</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>